      <!-- ── FAQ ── -->
      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2><%= state.name %> Income Tax FAQ</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              Does <%= state.name %> have a state income tax?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <% if (state.hasIncomeTax) { %>
                Yes. <%= state.name %> has a state income tax with a rate range of <%= state.brackets %>. The top rate is <%= state.topRate %>%. Actual state tax owed depends on your income, filing status, applicable deductions, credits, and state-specific rules.
              <% } else { %>
                <%= state.name %> does not have a broad-based state income tax. Residents do not pay a general state income tax on wages and salaries, though they may still owe federal income tax and other state or local taxes.
              <% } %>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              Does this calculator include <%= state.name %> state tax?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              This calculator estimates federal income tax only using 2025 federal brackets. It does not calculate your exact <%= state.name %> state income tax, which depends on state-specific rules, deductions, credits, and filing requirements. Use it for federal planning and review your state's department of revenue for a state tax estimate.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              Why does my refund estimate change when I adjust withholding?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              Your refund or balance owed is the difference between your estimated tax liability and the tax already withheld from your paychecks. Increasing withholding increases your estimated refund. Decreasing it increases your estimated balance owed. It is not extra money, just a change in when you pay.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              What is the difference between effective and marginal tax rate?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              Your marginal rate is the rate applied to the last dollar of taxable income. Your effective rate is total estimated federal tax divided by gross income. Most people's effective rate is significantly lower than their marginal rate because lower income is taxed at lower rates first.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              Can I use this for filing my taxes?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              No. This calculator is for educational planning estimates only. For filing, use official IRS forms, IRS Free File, commercial tax software, or a qualified tax professional familiar with <%= state.name %> tax rules.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
              What other taxes might <%= state.name %> residents owe?
              <span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              Beyond federal and state income tax, <%= state.name %> residents may also owe sales tax on purchases, property tax on real estate, local income or occupational taxes in some municipalities, and payroll taxes on wages. Self-employed residents also pay self-employment tax on net earnings.
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
